name: N-(4-pentynyl)phthalimide
Reason: The starting point for the prediction would be the melting point of phthalimide, which is approximately 231 degrees Celsius. The effects of various functional groups on the melting point need to be taken into account: (1) The alkynyl chain (pentynyl) being relatively linear and flexible tends to lower the melting point compared to the rigid and planar structure of phthalimide as it disrupts the crystalline lattice, decreasing intermolecular forces. An alkyl chain can decrease the melting point by about 40 to 80 degrees, but an alkyne might have a less pronounced effect due to its linearity and potential to align; let's estimate a decrease of around 60 degrees. (2) Alkylation on nitrogen can introduce steric hindrance and disrupt the hydrogen bonding capability; however, in this case N-alkylation does not involve any hydrogen-bond accepting or donating groups, thus its effect may be minimal; we might estimate a decrease of 5 degrees. Combining these estimated changes, the predicted melting point would be 231 - 60 - 5 = 166 degrees Celsius.
